In Tundra programming language, record fields are accessed with a dot opera
operator (.), not brackets like in JavaScript. And also note that, the type
type of 'total' is String since we didn't specify it as Number, so when add
adding 1 to it, "1" will be appended at the end which results in total outp
output as "201". To fix this issue you would need a similar function like p
parseNumber. However, Tundra does not have built-in functionality for parsi
parsing number from String and there is no standard way to convert string r
representation of numbers into actual numeric types. 

So instead of trying to write your own such parser we could take advantage 
of the fact that in Tundra you can implicitly coerce a value between compat
compatible types if necessary:

```tundra
def buildSelected(names, scores) {
  return {
    name: names[1],
    score: scores[0]
  };
}

val names = ["Ada", "Bea"];
val scores = [10, 20]; // changed string to int here.

val selected = buildSelected(names, scores);
var total = parseInt(selected.score) + 1; // added parseInt function
print(total);
```
This code will output the correct result `21` as we expected. Note that Tun
Tundra is a very minimalistic language and doesn't have full support for nu
number parsing, so it's not recommended to use this kind of features in pro
production grade applications. In real world cases you should use more robu
robust languages like JavaScript or Kotlin.
